		<hr size="1">It really depends on your level, what you are fighting, and what equipment that you have.  </P><P>The general rule is pick something that you can kill, take it to a safe spot (where you can zone if you need to and won't get adds), and kill it.</P><P>Typically you pull it to you with arrows if you have them or by running up and hitting it.  (Of course, none of us real paladins would ever hit the mob in the back to get at least one extra hit on the mob before it saw you.  Only warriors, sk, rogues, rangers, etc would do that.)  </P><P>If you are pulling with arrows, run backwards to your safe spot so you can keep shooting while you are getting to your safe spot.  (wait ignore all that archery stuff, you have to be a newbie to ask the question and thus would have no money for a bow and certainly not for lots of arrows)</P><P>When I was younger, I would often rotate weapons in fights.  I bought a PGT (Polished Granite Tomahawk) that would proc a berserker strength spell that made me take less damage.   Once it would proc, I would switch to a higher damage output weapon.  When the spell was done, switch back.  I am not sure if it was really that effective or not, but I never died while doing that and it seemed to keep my heath higher at the end of a fight.  </P><P>Of course once you get a little higher level, the normal trick to soloing is fight a mob until your health is going down, root it, heal, and fight some more.</P><P>Pick your enemies with care.  Paladins eventually are undead killers.  If you have a choice between an undead and live monster, all else being equal, kill the undead.  If you are using a Ghoulbane and Instrument of Nife, you will probably kill an undead twice as fast as a live monster, all else being equal.  </P><P>Choose what equipment and buffs you will use with care.  If soloing, you will probably not have much help, but if someone offers you a free buff ask for the appropriate one.  (if you have a ghoulbane and IoN, then dex buff may be more important than str buff, if fighting live monsters and you have no weapon that will proc, dex is no where near as important).  Likewise, if fighting cougars in IC, magic resistance is useless for any armor.  But if you are fighting splitpaw gnolls that have wizards and enchanters, magic resistance is high on the list of things to have.  </P><P>Know your location and have maps.  If you are soloing, you have to take care of yourself, there is no one to help you.  Know how to get to the zone and what to avoid on the way there.  (I wish I had remembered that the other night before I walked into two specs while heavily encumbered with no undead spells/buffs on or memorized.)</P><P>Read everlore and pay attention to anything said by Kohinoor, Nosferatu, Abazagaroth, and quite a few others.  Know eqatlas real well and their links to strategy for each zone.  <BR><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
</tr>
